## Rules

RULE 1  ‚Äî Every domain entity MUST be a named `Const`. Never rely on unnamed sort elements; Z3 would assign internal names like `Sort!val!0` that downstream code cannot reference.

RULE 2  ‚Äî `ForAll`/`Exists` quantifier list must be non-empty. `ForAll([], expr)` is a runtime error.

RULE 3  ‚Äî Bound variable must be a separate `Const` from all entity constants. Declare `v = Const('v', Sort)` (or `x`, `p`, etc.) and use it exclusively inside `ForAll`/`Exists`; never reuse an entity constant as a bound variable.

RULE 4  ‚Äî Universal claims ‚Üí `ForAll`; existential ‚Üí `Exists`; "No X is Y" ‚Üí `ForAll([v], Not(And(is_X(v), is_Y(v))))`. Conditional "if‚Ä¶then" ‚Üí `Implies`.
          Bare generic plurals: a bare plural subject without a determiner ("Vacuums suck", "Dogs bark", "Conductors perform") expresses a universal claim about the category ‚Äî NOT a fact about a singleton entity named after the category.
          ‚Üí `ForAll([v], Implies(is_vacuum(v), sucks(v)))`   ‚úì
          ‚Üí `sucks(Vacuums)`   ‚Üê treats the category name as a singleton entity   ‚úó
          Quick test: can you rephrase as "every [noun]‚Ä¶"? If yes ‚Üí `ForAll+Implies`.

RULE 5  ‚Äî No solver calls, no print statements, no assertions. Only declarations and assignments. Do NOT write `Solver()`, `s.check()`, `print(...)`, or `assert`.

RULE 6  ‚Äî Only `DeclareSort` is allowed. Never use `IntSort()`, `StringSort()`, `RealSort()`, or `SeqSort()`. Years, counts, and string-valued facts (channel names, titles, numeric quantities) must be modelled as named `Const` of a declared sort.

RULE 7  ‚Äî One NL property = one predicate. Each independently assertable property must be its own predicate. Never compress "private Ivy League research university" into one opaque predicate name ‚Äî declare `is_private`, `is_ivy_league`, `is_research` separately.

RULE 8  ‚Äî Every identifier used in `premises` or `q` must exactly match a previously declared name. Before finishing, verify every identifier inside `premises` and `q` was declared earlier with identical spelling.

RULE 9  ‚Äî `premises` must align one-to-one with the numbered NL premises: N premises in ‚Üí exactly N top-level formulas in `premises[]`, in the same order. Do not omit, merge, or split numbered premises.

RULE 10 ‚Äî Uninterpreted comparison predicates (`more_than`, `equal_to`, `no_more_than`, etc.) require mathematical axioms (asymmetry, transitivity) added as `background_constraints`. Omit `background_constraints` entirely if no comparison predicates are used.

RULE 11 ‚Äî Synonymous NL phrases must map to the SAME predicate name throughout. Different surface forms describing the same action or relation must share one predicate. For example, if P1 says "presents their work at the conference" and P2 refers to the same action, use `presents_work_at_conference` in both ‚Äî never two separate uninterpreted predicates. Splitting synonymous phrases silently breaks inference chains.

RULE 12 ‚Äî "X is a [noun/type]" means a TYPE predicate, never entity equality. Translate "X is a conductor" as `is_conductor(X)`, never as `X == conductor_entity`. Entity equality (`==`) is only correct for explicit identity statements like "X and Y are the same individual."

RULE 13 ‚Äî De Morgan negation scope: "neither A nor B" / "not A or B" with a SINGLE scoped
          negation over a disjunction means And(Not(A), Not(B)), NOT Or(Not(A), Not(B)).

          - "X is neither a cat nor a dog"  ‚Üí And(Not(is_cat(X)), Not(is_dog(X)))   ‚Üê De Morgan
          - "X is not a cat, or not a dog"  ‚Üí Or(Not(is_cat(X)), Not(is_dog(X)))    ‚Üê two separate negations

          Test: is there ONE "not" scoping over "A or B"?
            Yes ‚Üí And(Not(A), Not(B)).
            No, each clause carries its own negation ‚Üí Or(Not(A), Not(B)).

